{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"217d0376-65b3-4af8-b717-88c7a1f4e55f","content":"Yes, both are documented MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost Test History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test-ID generation strategy**. The default is now `FullyQualifiedName` (previously it was based on a legacy format). Azure DevOps tracks history by test ID, so all tests appear new.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `.runsettings` file (or update your existing one) to restore the old ID scheme:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\nOr, if you prefer to adopt the new IDs, accept the one-time history break and move forward.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer artificially associated with the first test. Accessing `TestName`, `TestResultsDirectory` (test-scoped), or similar properties now throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour code on line 13:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Remove or guard the access. If you need per-test setup, use `[TestInitialize]` instead:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // Only use class-scoped members here (e.g., context.DeploymentDirectory)\n}\n\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works fine here\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other v4 Breaking Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallelization** | Default is now `ExecutionScope.Class` (was sequential). Tests sharing static state may break. Set `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.Method)]` or disable. |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the test body only (not setup/cleanup). Infinite timeout constant removed. |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on collections** | Stricter type checking; some previously-passing comparisons may fail. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit numeric conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) no longer happen automatically. Match types exactly. |\n| **Namespace of entry point** | If using the new MSTest runner (`<UseVSTest>false</UseVSTest>`), ensure `Program.cs` isn't conflicting. |\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to fix the `ClassInitialize` issue?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4fd22476-1d54-4222-846d-b2cdba624ef8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has upgraded to MSTest v4 and is experiencing two issues:\n\n1. Tests appearing as new in Azure DevOps (lost history)\n2. `TestContext.TestName` throwing in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nLet me provide a comprehensive answer about known MSTest v4 breaking changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes I know about:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test ID** - MSTest v4 changed the default test ID format to use fully qualified names (namespace + class + method). This is what causes tests to appear as \"new\" in Azure DevOps because the test IDs no longer match the old ones. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in the runsettings file.\n\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** - Since `[ClassInitialize]` runs once per class before any individual test executes, the `TestContext` there has no associated test method, so accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. There's no active test to reference at that point in the lifecycle.\n3. I should also flag a few other breaking changes worth knowing about: `DeploymentItem` attribute behavior shifted, parallelization defaults may differ, `DataRow` now enforces strict type matching, and assembly-level attributes work differently than before.","outputTokens":1006,"requestId":"481A:1E89:1FD59F1:23964F3:69FC0110"},"id":"4edde894-6557-49a3-ae54-208cdf2a145a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:04:05.739Z","parentId":"53533bb1-327b-4547-89f6-c018f2d95b6d"}
